{"title_page": "Georgina Waylen", "text_new": "{{short description|British political scientist}}\n'''Georgina Nicola Alexandra Waylen''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|FBA|FAcSS}} (born 1959) is a British [[political scientist]], specialising in [[comparative politics]], [[political economy]], and [[Gender studies|gender and politics]]. Since April 2012, she has been Professor of Politics at the [[University of Manchester]]. She previously taught at the [[University of Sheffield]], the [[University of Salford]] and the [[University of East Anglia]]. She was a [[visiting scholar]] at the Minda de Gunzburg Center for European Studies, [[Harvard University]] from 2016 to 2017, and has been a visiting professor in the Department of Gender Studies at the [[London School of Economics]] since 2018.<ref name=\"bio Man\">{{cite web |title=Prof Georgina Waylen |url=https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/georgina.waylen.html |website=The University of Manchester |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bio CES\">{{cite web |title=Georgina Waylen |url=https://ces.fas.harvard.edu/people/georgina-waylen |website=Center for European Studies |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en |date=26 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bio LSE\">{{cite web |title=Georgina Waylen |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/gender/people/visiting-scholars/Georgina-Waylen |website=London School of Economics and Political Science |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWaylen studied politics and economics at the University of Manchester, graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in 1981.<ref name=\"bio AN\" /> She remained at Manchester to undertake postgraduate studies in political development between 1981 and 1983, graduating with a [[Master of Arts]] (MA) degree.<ref name=\"bio AN\" /> She then joined [[Huddersfield Polytechnic]] to undertake her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree.<ref name=\"bio AN\" /> Her [[doctoral thesis]] was titled \"British capital, local capital and the role of the state in the political economy of Jamaica 1920-1940\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Waylen |first1=Georgina Nicola Alexandra |title=British capital, local capital and the role of the state in the political economy of Jamaica 1920-1940 |url=https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.233575 |website=E-Thesis Online Service |publisher=The British Library |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=1988}}</ref> As Huddersfield Polytechnic did not have degree awarding powers, she was awarded her PhD by the [[Council for National Academic Awards]] (CNAA) in 1988.<ref name=\"bio AN\" />\n\n==Honours==\nWaylen was awarded the 2008 [[Victoria Schuck Award]] by the [[American Political Science Association]] for her book ''Engendering Transitions: Women\u2019s Mobilization, Institutions, and Gender Outcomes''.<ref>{{cite web |title=APSA Awards: Victoria Schuck Award Recipients |url=https://www.apsanet.org/schuckrecipients |website=American Political Science Association |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWaylen was elected a [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences]] (FAcSS) in 2010.<ref name=\"FAcSS\">{{cite web |title=Professor Georgina Waylen FAcSS |url=https://www.acss.org.uk/fellow/professor-georgina-waylen-facss/ |website=Academy of Social Sciences |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bio AN\">{{cite web |title=Prof. Georgina Waylen |url=http://www.academia-net.org/profil/prof-georgina-waylen/1154604 |website=AcademiaNet |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref> In July 2018, she was elected a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA), the United Kingdom's national academy for the humanities and social sciences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Record number of academics elected to British Academy |url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/news/record-number-academics-elected-british-academy |website=The British Academy |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en |date=20 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"FBA\">{{cite web |title=Professor Georgina Waylen |url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/georgina-waylen-FBA |website=The British Academy |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n\n* {{cite book |last1=Waylen |first1=Georgina |title=Gender in Third World politics |date=1996 |publisher=Open University Press |location=London |isbn=978-0335157709}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Waylen |first1=Georgina |title=Engendering transitions: women's mobilization, institutions, and gender outcomes |date=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0199248032 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/engenderingtrans0000wayl }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Waylen |editor1-first=Georgina |editor2-last=Celis |editor2-first=Karen |editor3-last=Kantola |editor3-first=Johanna |editor4-last=Weldon |editor4-first=Laurel |title=The Oxford handbook of gender and politics |date=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0199751457}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Waylen |editor1-first=Georgina |title=Gender and informal institutions |date=2017 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield International |location=Lanham, MD |isbn=978-1786600028}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{FBA 2018}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waylen, Georgina}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:Political science educators]]\n[[Category:Political economists]]\n[[Category:Gender studies academics]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Huddersfield]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British political scientist}}\n'''Georgina Nicola Alexandra Waylen''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|FBA|FAcSS}} (born 1959) is a British [[political scientist]], specialising in [[comparative politics]], [[political economy]], and [[Gender studies|gender and politics]]. Since April 2012, she has been Professor of Politics at the [[University of Manchester]]. She previously taught at the [[University of Sheffield]], the [[University of Salford]] and the [[University of East Anglia]]. She was a [[visiting scholar]] at the Minda de Gunzburg Center for European Studies, [[Harvard University]] from 2016 to 2017, and has been a visiting professor in the Department of Gender Studies at the [[London School of Economics]] since 2018.<ref name=\"bio Man\">{{cite web |title=Prof Georgina Waylen |url=https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/georgina.waylen.html |website=The University of Manchester |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"bio CES\">{{cite web |title=Georgina Waylen |url=https://ces.fas.harvard.edu/people/georgina-waylen |website=Center for European Studies |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en |date=26 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bio LSE\">{{cite web |title=Georgina Waylen |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/gender/people/visiting-scholars/Georgina-Waylen |website=London School of Economics and Political Science |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWaylen studied politics and economics at the University of Manchester, graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in 1981.<ref name=\"bio AN\" /> She remained at Manchester to undertake postgraduate studies in political development between 1981 and 1983, graduating with a [[Master of Arts]] (MA) degree.<ref name=\"bio AN\" /> She then joined [[Huddersfield Polytechnic]] to undertake her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree.<ref name=\"bio AN\" /> Her [[doctoral thesis]] was titled \"British capital, local capital and the role of the state in the political economy of Jamaica 1920-1940\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Waylen |first1=Georgina Nicola Alexandra |title=British capital, local capital and the role of the state in the political economy of Jamaica 1920-1940 |url=https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.233575 |website=E-Thesis Online Service |publisher=The British Library |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=1988}}</ref> As Huddersfield Polytechnic did not have degree awarding powers, she was awarded her PhD by the [[Council for National Academic Awards]] (CNAA) in 1988.<ref name=\"bio AN\" />\n\n==Honours==\nWaylen was awarded the 2008 Victoria Schuck Award by the [[American Political Science Association]] for her book ''Engendering Transitions: Women\u2019s Mobilization, Institutions, and Gender Outcomes''.<ref>{{cite web |title=APSA Awards: Victoria Schuck Award Recipients |url=https://www.apsanet.org/schuckrecipients |website=American Political Science Association |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWaylen was elected a [[Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences]] (FAcSS) in 2010.<ref name=\"FAcSS\">{{cite web |title=Professor Georgina Waylen FAcSS |url=https://www.acss.org.uk/fellow/professor-georgina-waylen-facss/ |website=Academy of Social Sciences |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bio AN\">{{cite web |title=Prof. Georgina Waylen |url=http://www.academia-net.org/profil/prof-georgina-waylen/1154604 |website=AcademiaNet |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref> In July 2018, she was elected a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA), the United Kingdom's national academy for the humanities and social sciences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Record number of academics elected to British Academy |url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/news/record-number-academics-elected-british-academy |website=The British Academy |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en |date=20 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"FBA\">{{cite web |title=Professor Georgina Waylen |url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/georgina-waylen-FBA |website=The British Academy |accessdate=27 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n\n* {{cite book |last1=Waylen |first1=Georgina |title=Gender in Third World politics |date=1996 |publisher=Open University Press |location=London |isbn=978-0335157709}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Waylen |first1=Georgina |title=Engendering transitions: women's mobilization, institutions, and gender outcomes |date=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0199248032 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/engenderingtrans0000wayl }}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Waylen |editor1-first=Georgina |editor2-last=Celis |editor2-first=Karen |editor3-last=Kantola |editor3-first=Johanna |editor4-last=Weldon |editor4-first=Laurel |title=The Oxford handbook of gender and politics |date=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0199751457}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Waylen |editor1-first=Georgina |title=Gender and informal institutions |date=2017 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield International |location=Lanham, MD |isbn=978-1786600028}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{FBA 2018}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waylen, Georgina}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:Political science educators]]\n[[Category:Political economists]]\n[[Category:Gender studies academics]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Huddersfield]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "+link", "url