{"title_page": "Lee Keun-shik", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean politician}}\n{{Korean name|[[Lee (Korean surname)|Lee]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image               = Mr. Lee Keun-shik.jpg\n| caption             = \n| name                = Lee Keun-shik\n| native_name         = {{nobold|\uc774\uadfc\uc2dd}}\n| native_name_lang    = ko\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1946|2|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Goseong County, South Gyeongsang|Goseong]], [[South Gyeongsang Province|South Gyeongsang]], [[South Korea]]\n| citizenship         = [[South Korea]]n\n| office1             = President of the [[Open Democrats]]\n| term_start1         = 8 March 2020\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = ''Position established''\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| constituency2       = [[Songpa District|Songpa]] 3rd\n| term_start2         = 30 May 2004\n| term_end2           = 29 May 2008\n| predecessor2        = ''Constituency established''\n| successor2          = [[Kim Sung-soon]]\n| office3             = [[Ministry of the Interior and Safety (South Korea)|Minister of Interior]]\n| president3          = [[Kim Dae-jung]]\n| term_start3         = 26 March 2001\n| term_end3           = 26 February 2003\n| predecessor3        = [[Choi In-ki]]\n| successor3          = [[Kim Doo-kwan]]\n| office4             = [[Ministry of the Interior and Safety (South Korea)|Deputy Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| president4          = [[Kim Young-sam]]<br>[[Kim Dae-jung]]\n| term_start4         = 6 March 1997\n| term_end4           = 3 March 1998\n| predecessor4        = [[Chung Tae-soo (1938)|Chung Tae-soo]]\n| successor4          = [[Seok Young-chul]] <small>(as Deputy Minister of Interior)</small>\n| office5             = [[Governor of South Gyeongsang Province|Deputy Governor of South Gyeongsang]]\n| governor5           = [[Kim Hyuk-kyu]]\n| term_start5         = 21 October 1994\n| term_end5           = 14 July 1995\n| predecessor5        = [[Chin Man-hyun]]\n| successor5          = [[Chung Chae-ryoong]]\n| office6             = Mayor of [[Geoje]]\n| term_start6         = 17 December 1983\n| term_end6           = 16 September 1985\n| predecessor6        = [[Park Chang-ki]]\n| successor6          = [[Ha Il-chung]]\n| party               = [[Open Democrats]]\n| otherparty          = [[Uri Party|Uri]] <small>(2004-2007)</small><br />[[Centrist Reformist and United New Party|CRUNP]] <small>(2007)</small><br />[[Centrist United Democratic Party|CUDP]] <small>(2007)</small><br />[[United New Democratic Party|UNDP]] <small>(2007-2008)</small><br />[[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2008)|UDP]] <small>(2008)</small><br />[[New Politics Alliance for Democracy|NPAD]] <small>(2014-2015)</small><br />[[Democratic Party of Korea|DP]] <small>(2015-2020)</small>\n| alma_mater          = [[Seoul National University]]\n| occupation          = Politician\n| spouse              = Huh Wee-soon\n| children            = 3\n}}\n\n'''Lee Keun-shik''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc774\uadfc\uc2dd, born 10 February 1946) is a [[South Korea]]n politician.\n\nBorn in [[Goseong County, South Gyeongsang|Goseong]], [[South Gyeongsang Province|South Gyeongsang]], Lee studied law at [[Seoul National University]].<ref name=\"lee\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 27 March 2001|title= <\ud504\ub85c\ud544> \uc774\uadfc\uc2dd \ud589\uc815\uc790\uce58\ubd80 \uc7a5\uad00|url= http://www.dt.co.kr/contents.html?article_no=2001032702100252579001|work= |location= |access-date= 8 March 2020}}</ref> After passing the Civil Service Examination in 1971, he started his career at the [[Economic Planning Board]] (now as the [[Ministry of Economy and Finance (South Korea)|Ministry of Economy and Finance]]).<ref name=\"ks\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 11 September 2018|title= \uac74\uad6d\ub300, \uc774\uadfc\uc2dd \uc804 \ud589\uc815\uc790\uce58\ubd80 \uc7a5\uad00 \uc11d\uc88c\uad50\uc218\ub85c \ucd08\ube59|url= http://www.newstopia.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=24953|work= |location= |access-date= 8 March 2020}}</ref> He served as the Mayor of [[Geoje]], Deputy Governor of South Gyeongsang, Secretary to the President for Civil Affairs, Deputy Minister of Home Affairs<ref name=\"lee\"/> and Minister of Interior.<ref name=\"ks\"/> He was also the one-term [[National Assembly (South Korea)|Member of the National Assembly]] from 2004 to 2008.<ref name=\"ks\"/>\n\nLee had received an honorary degree from Samarkand State Institute of Foreign Languages in [[Uzbekistan]].<ref name=\"ks\"/> On 8 March 2020, he was elected as the President of the newly-formed [[Open Democrats]].<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 8 March 2020|title= \uc815\ubd09\uc8fc \uc8fc\ub3c4 '\uc5f4\ub9b0\ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9' \uacf5\uc2dd \ucd9c\ubc94\u2026\uc774\uadfc\uc2dd \ub300\ud45c \ucd94\ub300|url= https://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/5304234|work= |location= |access-date= 8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:Mr. Lee Keun-shik.jpg|none|thumb|Congressman Lee Keun-shik in a meeting with Open Democrats party leaders (Center)]]\n<br />\n\n== Election results ==\n=== General elections ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Constituency !! Political party !! Votes (%) !! Remarks\n|-\n| 2000 || [[Tongyeong]]-[[Goseong County, South Gyeongsang|Goseong]] || [[Millennium Democratic Party|MDP]] || 9,027 (9.72%) || Defeated\n|-\n| 2004 || [[Songpa District|Songpa]] 3rd || [[Uri Party|Uri]] || 41,205 (38.23%) || '''Won'''\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://twitter.com/powerkslee Lee Keun-shik] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/powerkslee Lee Keun-shik] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://blog.naver.com/powerkslee Lee Keun-shik] on [[Blog]]\n\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South Korean politicians]]\n[[Category:Seoul National University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from South Gyeongsang Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean politician}}\n{{Korean name|[[Lee (Korean surname)|Lee]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image               = Mr. Lee Keun-shik.jpg\n| caption             = \n| name                = Lee Keun-shik\n| native_name         = {{nobold|\uc774\uadfc\uc2dd}}\n| native_name_lang    = ko\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1946|2|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Goseong County, South Gyeongsang|Goseong]], [[South Gyeongsang Province|South Gyeongsang]], [[South Korea]]\n| citizenship         = [[South Korea]]n\n| office1             = President of the [[Open Democrats]]\n| term_start1         = 8 March 2020\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = ''Position established''\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| constituency2       = [[Songpa District|Songpa]] 3rd\n| term_start2         = 30 May 2004\n| term_end2           = 29 May 2008\n| predecessor2        = ''Constituency established''\n| successor2          = [[Kim Sung-soon]]\n| office3             = [[Ministry of the Interior and Safety (South Korea)|Minister of Interior]]\n| president3          = [[Kim Dae-jung]]\n| term_start3         = 26 March 2001\n| term_end3           = 26 February 2003\n| predecessor3        = [[Choi In-ki]]\n| successor3          = [[Kim Doo-kwan]]\n| office4             = [[Ministry of the Interior and Safety (South Korea)|Deputy Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| president4          = [[Kim Young-sam]]<br>[[Kim Dae-jung]]\n| term_start4         = 6 March 1997\n| term_end4           = 3 March 1998\n| predecessor4        = [[Chung Tae-soo (1938)|Chung Tae-soo]]\n| successor4          = [[Seok Young-chul]] <small>(as Deputy Minister of Interior)</small>\n| office5             = [[Governor of South Gyeongsang Province|Deputy Governor of South Gyeongsang]]\n| governor5           = [[Kim Hyuk-kyu]]\n| term_start5         = 21 October 1994\n| term_